The strainer-plate (only) from a strainer bowl, found within the posthole, but now in many fragments as much of the metal has perished. Bowls with similar strainer-plates come from: A) the Welwyn Garden City rich burial of the late C1st BC (Stead 1967, 25), B) the Crownthorpe hoard (unpublished), C) the Stanway Doctor burial (Crummy et al, forthcoming), D) Alchester fortress ditch (E. Sauer, pers. comm), and E) a well at Blain, Loire-Atlantique (S. Corson, pers comm). B-E all date to c 40-55 AD. A peltate foot, like those on C) has also been found in the same Object (50046). Foot and plate may well be from a carinated bowl like B-E, and together with D from Alchester define a western limit to the form, which also occurs in pottery among the Trinovantes/Catuvellauni.

COLEM: C060157. Date in: ---03-06. Date finished: 19-05-06. Condition: Embedded in soil block. Appears to have been folded as are two layers separated by soil, with evidence of crushing/crumpling at some edges. The majority is completely mineralised and consists of powdery pale green corrosion stain on the soil surface, with faint semi-circular imprint surviving in soil around the upper folded half, delineating the edge. Has more intact fragments at edges of lower section, which retain some traces of metal in their core. These have a roughened friable grey metallic surface, but are pitted with pale friable turquoise corrosion and are extremely fragile. Cracks and splits run between each perforation and they have no structural intregity; the sheet having disintegrated in the block. Various small fragments randomly in surrounding soil. Has a layer of dark compacted organic material against each fragment, and traces of this layer run, with some discontinuation, throughout the entire soil block.

Only some fragments were strong enough to remove and stabilise. Treatment: Removed from soil - small handtools. Degreased - acetone. Stablised - BTA, 3% in vacuum. Rinsed - IMS. Dried - air. Lacquered - Incralac, 50% in IMS.

Base of a grey-ware ?jar with the junction between wall and base trimmed to a fairly consistent height.  The use of pottery counters is far from certain, particularly when they are, like this one, much larger than bone or glass board-game counters. Various ideas have been put forward (Crummy 1983, 93-4):  a) tally counters - a relief from Trier supports this idea as it shows a man moving discs on a tray, interpreted as counters on a reckoning board (MacGregor 1978, 33; Chardron-Picault 2004, figs 15-16); b) mats for hot pots (very large and thick ones made from tile or dolium sherds are ideal for this purpose); c) lids for narrow-mouthed jars - a few examples have been found in situ (H. Major, pers. comm); d) counters for a game comparable to merrels played on 'boards' scratched in the earth; e) a set with the pieces graded in diameter found in Colchester has been identified as a child's stacking toy (Colchester Archaeologist 11, 34); f) work in France has noted that they are often concentrated on sanctuary sites and in urban workshop zones, raising the possibility that they were produced as a secondary product by artisans who sold them to worshippers for use as votive offerings (Tuffreau-Libre 1994, 128-37; Chardron-Picault 2004, 335-7); g) some, of course, were pierced and used as spindlewhorls - Roman sherds were often selected for this purpose in the Migration Period; roughly-shaped counters may therefore be unfinished spindlewhorls.  Given the diversity in size and finish of the counters, and the diversity in their archaeological context and associations, it seems most likely that different sizes, with different degrees of finish, were used in different ways. Their inclusion under the Keyword 'Recreation' is therefore a matter of convenience, rather than accurate identification of function. [N Crummy, 11/03/06]  References P. Chardron-Picault, 'Les rondelles en terre cuite mises au jour dans le quartier artisanal du 'Lycee Militaire' a Augustodunum (Autun, Saone-et-Loire)' in Societe Francaise d'Etude de la Ceramique Antique en Gaule, Actes du Congres de Vallauris 20-23 mai 2004, 329-340 Colchester Archaeologist - magazine of The Colchester Archaeological Trust N. Crummy 1983, The Roman small finds from excavations in Colchester 1971-9, Colchester Archaeological Report 2 A. MacGregor 1978, Roman finds from Skeldersgate and Bishophill, The Archaeology of York 17/2 M. Tuffreau-Libre 1994, 'La ceramique dans les sanctuaires gallo-romains', in Les sanctuaires de tradition indigene en Gaule romaine, Actes du colloque d'Argentomagus de 1992

Fragmenting hollow object, probably iron-working debris.

This object was analysed at Bradford University, Dept of Archaeological Science, using XRF. The only metal present was iron.

Bradford University results from the XRF analysis of a small piece of possible crucible.

The date of the sherd is presumed to be Roman, and would therefore be expected to contain traces of copper alloy if it was indeed a fragment from a crucible. The sherd was analysed using XRF (x-ray fluoresence) for the presence of copper, tin, lead and other alloying agents such as zinc. Energy dispersive x-ray analysis (EDAX) determined that none of these elements were present, with no characteristic peak at 8.0 Kev visible for copper. The peaks visible are those for iron Ka at 6.4 Kev, iron Kb at 7.06 Kev, the peak at just over 3 KEV, which is probably calcium, and the peak at 16 Kev which is from the equipment's screen. It must therefore be concluded that the pottery sherd is not from a crucible, albeit not one that has been used in the copper alloy process.

Complete bow brooch. Long slender front, with a bulb at the end. No decoration visible. Fastened pin is in catchplate. Wide lugs. Polden Hill enamelled - mid 1st century (Crummy 25/11/03). [sig:30/09/2003 SWILLIAMS] ---- Complete. Sprung south-western T-shaped brooch with Polden Hill type mechanism. The chord is held in a large leaf-shaped rearhook, which is part of a group of stout foliate mouldings on the top of the head. There is chequered enamel on the upper half of the bow. The foot is long and tapers to a small knob. The junction with the bow has a pair of leaf-shaped mouldings and-a pair of low linear mouldings run down the length of the foot. Upper part of catchplate damaged. See Hull Type 110. Late 1st-mid 2nd century. Most similar to brooches from Sea Mills & Warwick. [sig:09/11/2004 NCRUMMY]

Very fragmented pieces of what may be copper alloy, but tinged with red (possibly enamel?) Layered inside a lump of possible mortar. 2005. [sig:Sandie Williams 21.3.2006]  Small fragments of thin sheet of red glass, presumably from a vessel, but there is some possibility that, if the fragments represent more than one piece of sheet, they may have been used as decorative insets. Much later examples of such a use are the 4th-century headbands from Lankhills and Colchester (Clarke 1979, 317' Crummy 1983, no. 1799; Crummy, Crummy & Crossan 1993, 145, grave 404).  The copper-alloy elements mentioned by S. Williams (above) are corrosion products produced by the red colourant.   NB - Send on to D. Allen for her opinion. (N. Crummy, 25/04/06)

Copper alloy handle/blunt dissector end of a double ended surgical instrument, with the remains of the iron scalpel blade in the squared end of the instrument. Type 1 form. Leaf-shaped blade with slight medial ridge. Handle is of octagonal section leading to a squared section. Scalpel end has a rolled end a v-shaped tang to insert the iron blade. Possible enamelled object. Object is very fragmented with copper alloy elements and possible fragments of red enamel. (S. Williams)  Small fragments of thin sheet of red glass, presumably from a vessel, but there is some possibility that, if the fragments represent more than one piece of sheet, they may have been used as decorative insets. Much later examples of such a use are the 4th-century headbands from Lankhills and Colchester (Clarke 1979, 317' Crummy 1983, no. 1799; Crummy, Crummy & Crossan 1993, 145, grave 404).  The copper-alloy elements mentioned by S. Williams (above) are corrosion products produced by the red colourant.   NB - Send on to D. Allen for her opinion. (N. Crummy, 6/4/06)
